.SH "NAME"
mksfx.sh \- make SelFeXtractor archive
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
\&\fBmksfx.sh\fR [\fB\-x\fR \fIsfxname\fR] [\fB\-c\fR \fIcompression\fR] [\fB\-r\fR \fIrunname\fR] [\fIdirectory\fR]
.SH "OPTIONS"
.IX Header "OPTIONS"
.IP "\fIdirectory\fR" 4
.IX Item "directory"
name of the directory to compress ( default : current directory )
.IP "\fB\-x\fR \fIsfxname\fR, \fB\-\-sfx=\fR\fIsfxname\fR" 4
.IX Item "-x sfxname, --sfx=sfxname"
file name to create ( default : same as for directory )
.IP "\fB\-c\fR \fIcompression\fR, \fB\-\-compress=\fR\fIcompression\fR" 4
.IX Item "-c compression, --compress=compression"
compression method, could be : \fBgzip\fR, \fBbzip2\fR ( default : \fBgzip\fR )
.IP "\fB\-r\fR \fIrunname\fR, \fB\-\-run=\fR\fIrunname\fR" 4
.IX Item "-r runname, --run=runname"
name of the file to run after uncompressing ( default : run.sh )
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
Compress the archived content of a directory, then add an autoextract head to the file, so it will look and act as a \fIbash\fR\|(1) script. The executable head is kept small
and simple, so there are no paranoia checkings included.
.PP
When the current directory is compressed, the script will exclude itself from the archive.
.PP
When the selfextractor is executed, it's header part will decompress it's data part to a random named temporary directory in the \fI/tmp/\fR directory, then if an autorun
script exist, will run it.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.IX Header "SEE ALSO"
\&\fIbash\fR\|(1), \fIgzip\fR\|(1), \fIbzip2\fR\|(1), \fItar\fR\|(1);  \fIsed\fR\|(1), \fIgrep\fR\|(1), \fImktemp\fR\|(1)
